新闻媒体、组织和公众使用社交媒体来传播有关大流行的有效信息和错误信息。<ref name="BMJ1">{{Cite journal|script-title=Covid-19: how to be careful with trust and expertise on social media|trans-title=Covid-19：如何谨慎对待社交媒体上的信任和专业知识|author=|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m1160|last=Llewellyn|first=Sue|date=2020-03-25|journal=BMJ|issue=|doi=10.1136/bmj.m1160|others=|year=|volume=368|page=|pages=m1160|pmid=32213480|via=www.bmj.com|doi-access=free|access-date=2020-10-04|archive-date=2021-01-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210117113251/https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m1160|dead-url=no}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|script-title=How to fight an infodemic |trans-title=如何应对信息流行病|author=|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30461-X/abstract|last=Zarocostas|first=John|date=2020-02-29|journal=The Lancet|issue=10225|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30461-X|others=|year=|volume=395|page=676|language=en|issn=0140-6736|pmc=7133615|pmid=32113495}}</ref> CDC、WHO、医学期刊和卫生保健组织已与Facebook、Google Scholar、TikTok<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/28/21158276/coronavirus-covid19-tiktok-who-world-health-organization-protection|script-title=The World Health Organization has joined TikTok to fight coronavirus misinformation|trans-title=世界卫生组织已加入TikTok，以应对冠状病毒错误信息|last=Kelly|first=Makena|date=2020-02-28|work=The Verge|author=|publisher=|accessdate=|language=|format=|archive-date=2021-01-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210117113341/https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/28/21158276/coronavirus-covid19-tiktok-who-world-health-organization-protection|dead-url=no}}</ref>和Twitter合作，在众多平台上更新和传播信息。其他人，例如纽约医院系统中的急诊医学主治医生，都在使用其社交媒体帐户举报与COVID-19作战的第一手资料。<ref name=":22">{{cite web|script-title=Harnessing Social Media for the COVID-19 Pandemic|trans-title=利用社交媒体应对COVID-19大流行|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/harnessing-social-media-for-the-covid-19-pandemic/|accessdate=|author=|date=|last=Iwai|first=Yoshiko|format=|publisher=|language=en|website=Scientific American Blog Network|access-date=2020-04-21|archive-date=2020-04-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421050327/https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/harnessing-social-media-for-the-covid-19-pandemic/|dead-url=no}}</ref> 据4月8日报道，根据1月1日至3月19日的社会倾听研究，围绕COVID-19疾病状况的谈话内容在医疗保健专业人员周围增加了1000％，在消费者中增加了2500％。<ref>{{cite web|script-title=Docs are talking about COVID-19 on social media—and pharma is looking for lessons|trans-title=Docs在社交媒体上谈论COVID-19，而pharma正在寻找教训|url=https://www.fiercepharma.com/marketing/social-listening-survey-finds-hcp-activity-way-up-around-covid-19-and-pharma-looking-for|accessdate=|author=|date=2020-04-08|last=Syner Bulik|first=Beth|format=|publisher=|language=en|website=FiercePharma|dead-url=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210117113304/https://www.fiercepharma.com/marketing/social-listening-survey-finds-hcp-activity-way-up-around-covid-19-and-pharma-looking-for|archive-date=2021-01-17|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> 试点研究调查了美国对科学的信任度是否在2019年12月至2020年3月之间发生了变化，并认为公开讨论和研究，现状会有所改善，但该研究报告没有找到。<ref>{{cite journal|script-title=Assessing changes in US public trust in science amid the COVID-19 pandemic |trans-title=评估COVID-19大流行期间美国公众对科学的信任变化|author=|url=|first1=Jon|date=2020|journal=Public Health|issue=|doi=10.1016/j.puhe.2020.05.004|others=|year=|volume=183|page=|pages=122–125|pmc=7218345|pmid=32405095|last1=Agley}}</ref>

